{"key":"post-16333003","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16333003</id>\n<content>I've yet to find a mushroom producing mycelium whether sclerotia producing or not which benefits in any way from colonization in total darkness.&amp;nbsp; One book 30 years ago spouted that nonsense and people have been acting like Moses carried it off the mountain ever since. &lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shrug.gif&quot; alt=&quot;:shrug:&quot; title=&quot;:shrug:&quot;/&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Thanks for posting.&amp;nbsp; Colonization and sclerotia production are somewhat faster in the presence of low level ambient light from day of inoculation.&amp;nbsp; Don't use 24/7 light as it will slow down both.&amp;nbsp; Just let your projects get normal ambient room light, but no direct sunlight or bright fluorescent light until the fruiting stage.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16333203</next>\n<prev>16332945</prev>\n<first>16328051</first>\n<last>20056685</last>\n<when>1338861408</when>\n<utime>06/05/12 04:56 AM</utime>\n</post>"}